AB  - In addition to perceptions of public opinion, individuals' readiness to voice personal opinions publicly is often subject to social context. For example, in authoritarian countries, people's willingness to voice opinions may be a function of their perceptions of the government's stance, and individuals are likely to refrain from expressing opinions that appear to contradict the authority. However, this tendency does not indicate that individuals' perceptions of public opinion are not relevant in such a context. On the contrary, individuals' perceptions of public support have such an impact that even authoritarian states have to concern themselves with managing perceived public opinion. For example, state-owned media in authoritarian regimes tend to highlight the consensus among people and the popularity of policies and political leadership (Chang, 1999). This tendency reflects the attempts of authoritarian governments to influence not only the opinions of individuals but also their perceptions of public opinion regarding government policies and leadership. Thus, how perceptions of the authority and perceived public opinion may be concurrently associated with people's opinion expression in such a context becomes an intriguing question. Singapore, which ranks 149th in the world press freedom index (Reporters without Borders, 2013), provides an ideal location for such an examination. Although it permits private ownership of the press, the Singapore government requires the press to renew their permits and licenses annually. The government also controls operations within the press by requiring newspapers to issue management shares (which command voting powers that are 200 times greater than that of ordinary shares) only to parties that are approved by the government (Tan & Soh, 1994). Such a context enables us to observe how a regulated press system interacts with the public's exposure to news, perception of public opinion, and expression of personal opinion. We choose the ongoing debate regarding lifting the ban on the sale of human organs in Singapore as the context of this study. Organ trading is a controversial topic that has been intensely debated in many countries, including Singapore, where the waiting list for a kidney transplant is up to nine years because of the scarcity of donors (Ritter, 2008). Supporters of organ trading argue that it is not wrong to offer monetary incentives to potential living donors, provided that a competent doctor has first determined that there are no health risks. However, opponents are concerned that only wealthy patients will be able to afford organs and that the poor will be the primary sellers, which will further jeopardize their health (January 18, 2007, The Straits Times, page H6). In contrast to the polarized perspectives presented by the two contending factions, the position assumed by the Singapore government appears rather ambiguous. Singapore has retained its strict penalties against organ trading and has declared that offering financial incentives for organ donation is morally and legally wrong (Channel News Asia, 2009). Nevertheless, the government permits financial reimbursement to living donors and has urged citizens to carefully review the idea of legalizing organ sales rather than utterly rejecting the notion (Tan & Tan, 2008). In view of the ambivalent messages sent by the government, Singaporeans' interpretations of the government's position may lean in either direction, which allows us to examine how perceptions of the news reports are associated with various interpretations of governmental opinion and affect individuals' opinion perception and expression. Adapted from the source document.
