AB  - Amitia Etzioni pondered privacy rights in The Limits of Privacy (1999). He returns to the topic in Privacy in a Cyber Age: Policy and Practice, this time focusing on new technologies for government to gather and analyze data. Privacy against government, Etzioni believes, provides fertile ground for his communitarian philosophy of split differences, moderation, reasonableness. The Constitution phrases many rights in absolute terms: "Congress shall make no law abridging the freedom of speech." The Fourth Amendment, by contrast, protects against "unreasonable searches and seizures." Reasonable searches are permissible and unreasonable ones aren't, which, according to Etzioni, makes the Fourth Amendment "a prime example of a liberal communitarian text." You needn't embrace Etzioni's prescriptions for Fourth Amendment jurisprudence to share his view that the doctrine needs revamping. Start with "reasonable expectation of privacy," the oft-applied test that first arose in Katz v. United States (1967). At issue in Katz was a recording device placed atop a phone booth, where it¬ picked up the defendants half of an incriminating call. Did police need¬ a warrant? The government said no: The Fourth Amendment might apply inside the booth, but the recorder was outside, in the elements. But¬ the Supreme Court rejected the inside-outside line and declared that "the Fourth Amendment protects people, not places." In a concurring opinion, Justice John Marshall Harlan remarked that the Fourth Amendments applicability depends on whether the person had "a reasonable¬ expectation of privacy." That phrase has been the heart of Fourth Amendment law for nearly 50 years.
